  <article class="article-body">

    <p>When people hear "deployment platform with agents on nodes, reconciliation loops, and Envoy for routing," the first question is often: "why not just use Kubernetes?"</p>

    <p>It's a fair question. Kubernetes solves container orchestration at massive scale. It has a reconciliation model, a proxy layer (kube-proxy), service discovery, rolling updates, and health checks. devopsellence reimplements some of these ideas at a smaller scale, using Docker directly instead of the Kubernetes stack.</p>

    <p>This article explains why.</p>

    <h2>What Kubernetes requires</h2>

    <p>To run a Kubernetes cluster, you need:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>etcd</strong> &mdash; a distributed key-value store for cluster state. Requires at least 3 nodes for high availability. Needs backup, monitoring, and disk performance tuning.</li>
      <li><strong>kube-apiserver</strong> &mdash; the API server that all components talk to. Needs TLS certificates, authentication configuration, RBAC policies, and admission controllers.</li>
      <li><strong>kube-scheduler</strong> &mdash; decides which node runs each pod based on resource requests, affinity rules, taints, and topology constraints.</li>
      <li><strong>kube-controller-manager</strong> &mdash; runs controllers for ReplicaSets, Deployments, Services, and other resources.</li>
      <li><strong>kubelet</strong> &mdash; the agent on each node that manages pods and containers via the container runtime (containerd).</li>
      <li><strong>kube-proxy</strong> &mdash; configures iptables or IPVS rules on each node for service routing.</li>
      <li><strong>CNI plugin</strong> &mdash; Calico, Cilium, Flannel, or another network plugin for pod-to-pod networking across nodes.</li>
      <li><strong>Ingress controller</strong> &mdash; Nginx Ingress, Traefik, or similar for HTTP routing.</li>
      <li><strong>cert-manager</strong> &mdash; for automated TLS certificate management.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Then, for each application, you write:</p>

    <ul>
      <li>A <code>Deployment</code> manifest with resource requests/limits, readiness probes, liveness probes, and rolling update strategy.</li>
      <li>A <code>Service</code> manifest to expose the pods.</li>
      <li>An <code>Ingress</code> (or <code>Gateway</code>) manifest for HTTP routing.</li>
      <li>A <code>Secret</code> or external secret operator configuration.</li>
      <li>A <code>HorizontalPodAutoscaler</code> if you want auto-scaling.</li>
      <li>Optionally: <code>NetworkPolicy</code>, <code>PodDisruptionBudget</code>, <code>PodSecurityStandard</code>, and more.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>This is a lot of infrastructure to stand up and operate. For large organizations with platform teams, it's justified &mdash; the abstraction power is enormous. For a team of 2-10 engineers deploying a Rails app and a Sidekiq worker, it's a full-time job that isn't building your product.</p>

    <h2>What devopsellence requires</h2>

    <p>On each server:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Docker</strong> &mdash; the standard container runtime. Ships with every major Linux distribution. One <code>apt install docker.io</code> or equivalent.</li>
      <li><strong>The devopsellence agent</strong> &mdash; a single Go binary. Installed via <code>curl | bash</code> with a bootstrap token.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>That's it. The agent manages everything else: pulling images, running containers, configuring Envoy (which it runs as a Docker container), managing TLS certificates, resolving secrets, and reporting status.</p>

    <p>There is no cluster. No etcd. No API server. No scheduler. No CNI plugin. No YAML manifests. Each server is independent. The agent connects to the control plane (a hosted service), fetches what should be running, and makes it so.</p>

    <h2>Why Docker and not containerd directly</h2>

    <p>The agent uses Docker's API (via the official <code>moby/moby</code> Go client) rather than talking to containerd directly. The reasons are practical:</p>

    <p><strong>Docker provides the right abstraction level.</strong> The agent needs to: pull images with registry authentication, create containers with environment variables and port bindings, manage container lifecycle (start, stop, remove), inspect container state, and connect containers to a shared network. Docker's API does all of this with well-documented, stable endpoints. containerd's API is lower-level &mdash; you'd need to manage image unpacking, snapshot mounting, and networking yourself.</p>

    <p><strong>Docker is universal.</strong> Every Linux server that runs containers has Docker (or a compatible drop-in like Podman with the Docker socket). Operators know how to install it, debug it, and monitor it. <code>docker ps</code>, <code>docker logs</code>, <code>docker exec</code> work everywhere. Using Docker means the agent doesn't add unfamiliar tooling to your server.</p>

    <p><strong>Docker's networking is sufficient.</strong> The agent creates a Docker bridge network that all managed containers join. Containers can reach each other by name. Envoy routes traffic to the web container's internal IP. For devopsellence's model (one app environment per node, 2-3 containers), Docker networking is simple and reliable. There's no need for a CNI plugin or overlay network.</p>

    <p>containerd would save one layer of abstraction (Docker's daemon sits on top of containerd). But that layer provides image management, networking, and lifecycle APIs that the agent would need to reimplement. The overhead of Docker's daemon is negligible for a node running 2-3 containers.</p>

    <h2>What Kubernetes gives you that devopsellence doesn't</h2>

    <p>Kubernetes genuinely solves problems that devopsellence doesn't attempt:</p>

    <p><strong>Multi-tenant bin-packing.</strong> Running 200 microservices efficiently across 50 nodes requires a scheduler that understands resource requests, affinity, anti-affinity, and topology. devopsellence has no scheduler because it doesn't pack multiple workloads onto one node.</p>

    <p><strong>Automatic horizontal pod autoscaling.</strong> HPA can scale pods based on CPU, memory, or custom metrics. devopsellence doesn't auto-scale &mdash; you add or remove nodes manually (or via your own automation).</p>

    <p><strong>Service mesh and service discovery.</strong> Kubernetes, combined with a service mesh like Istio or Linkerd, provides mutual TLS between services, traffic splitting, circuit breaking, and observability. devopsellence runs one app per node and doesn't need service-to-service routing.</p>

    <p><strong>Ecosystem.</strong> Helm charts, operators, CRDs, and the entire CNCF ecosystem. If you need Kafka, PostgreSQL, Redis, and Elasticsearch all managed as Kubernetes resources, the ecosystem is unmatched.</p>

    <p><strong>Multi-cloud and hybrid portability.</strong> Kubernetes runs on every cloud provider and on bare metal. A single cluster can span environments with federation. devopsellence currently targets individual servers, not cluster-level abstractions.</p>

    <h2>What devopsellence gives you that Kubernetes doesn't</h2>

    <p><strong>Zero cluster overhead.</strong> There is no cluster to operate. No etcd to back up. No API server to monitor. No upgrade path to plan. The control plane is a hosted service, and the node runtime is a single binary plus a few managed containers. You manage your servers and your application code. Everything in between is handled.</p>

    <p><strong>Familiar debugging.</strong> When something goes wrong, you SSH into your server and use tools you already know: <code>docker ps</code>, <code>docker logs</code>, <code>journalctl</code>, <code>top</code>, <code>curl</code>. There's no <code>kubectl</code> to learn, no pod/container distinction to navigate, no CrashLoopBackOff to decode.</p>

    <p><strong>Single-command deploy.</strong> <code>devopsellence deploy</code> builds, pushes, and publishes your existing Dockerized app. You still keep your Dockerfile, but you do not also need Helm charts and Kubernetes manifests to describe the same deployment. No <code>kubectl apply</code> followed by <code>kubectl rollout status</code>. One command, one outcome.</p>

    <p><strong>TLS private key locality.</strong> As covered in our <%= link_to "GCP primitives series", blog_post_path(slug: "gcp-primitives-part-5-tls") %>, the agent generates TLS keys locally. Kubernetes typically requires the ingress controller (or cert-manager) to hold private keys centrally.</p>

    <p><strong>Control plane independence.</strong> The control plane can be down for hours without affecting running applications. Agents continue from cached state. In Kubernetes, if the API server goes down, kubectl stops working, new pods can't be scheduled, and some controllers stop functioning. Existing pods continue running, but the cluster's self-healing capabilities are degraded.</p>

    <h2>When to choose which</h2>

    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
        <span class="terminal-bar-title">Decision framework</span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <pre class="config-pre"><code>Choose Kubernetes when:
  - You run 10+ distinct services
  - You have a platform team (or want to build one)
  - You need auto-scaling, service mesh, or multi-tenant isolation
  - Your infrastructure budget justifies cluster overhead
  - You're already invested in the CNCF ecosystem

Choose devopsellence when:
  - You run 1-5 applications
  - Your team is 2-15 engineers, not a platform org
  - You want git-push deploys with production security
  - You manage your own servers (VPS, bare metal, home lab)
  - You don't want to operate a cluster to run a web app</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>These aren't competing tools for the same use case. Kubernetes is infrastructure for running many workloads at scale. devopsellence is VM-native deployment tooling for teams that want better ways to run applications on servers they already control. The overlap is narrow &mdash; and in that overlap, the question is usually about team size and operational willingness, not technical capability.</p>

    <h2>Docker as a foundation</h2>

    <p>By building on Docker directly, devopsellence keeps the stack short: your code, a Dockerfile, Docker on the server, the agent, and Envoy. Each layer is widely understood, well-documented, and independently debuggable. You don't need to understand containerd's snapshotter interface or Kubernetes' informer cache to debug a deployment. You need to understand Docker and your application.</p>

    <p>The simplest infrastructure that meets your requirements is the best infrastructure. For a single web application on a few servers, Docker is that simplest infrastructure. Kubernetes adds power you might need one day, but it adds it today, as operational cost you pay every day.</p>

